ENTRY       EC 2.5.1.41                 Enzyme
NAME        phosphoglycerol geranylgeranyltransferase;
            glycerol phosphate geranylgeranyltransferase;
            geranylgeranyl-transferase;
            prenyltransferase;
            (S)-3-O-geranylgeranylglyceryl phosphate synthase;
            (S)-geranylgeranylglyceryl phosphate synthase;
            GGGP synthase;
            (S)-GGGP synthase;
            GGGPS;
            geranylgeranyl diphosphate:sn-glyceryl phosphate geranylgeranyltransferase;
            geranylgeranyl diphosphate:sn-glycerol-1-phosphate geranylgeranyltransferase
CLASS       Transferases;
            Transferring alkyl or aryl groups, other than methyl groups;
            Transferring alkyl or aryl groups, other than methyl groups (only sub-subclass identified to date)
SYSNAME     geranylgeranyl-diphosphate:sn-glycerol-1-phosphate geranylgeranyltransferase
REACTION    geranylgeranyl diphosphate + sn-glycerol 1-phosphate = diphosphate + 3-(O-geranylgeranyl)-sn-glycerol 1-phosphate [RN:R04158]
ALL_REAC    R04158
SUBSTRATE   geranylgeranyl diphosphate [CPD:C00353];
            sn-glycerol 1-phosphate [CPD:C00623]
PRODUCT     diphosphate [CPD:C00013];
            3-(O-geranylgeranyl)-sn-glycerol 1-phosphate [CPD:C04590]
COMMENT     This cytosolic enzyme catalyses the first pathway-specific step in the biosynthesis of the core membrane diether lipids in archaebacteria [2]. Requires Mg2+ for maximal activity [2]. It catalyses the alkylation of the primary hydroxy group in sn-glycerol 1-phosphate by geranylgeranyl diphosphate (GGPP) in a prenyltransfer reaction where a hydroxy group is the nucleophile in the acceptor substrate [2]. The other enzymes involved in the biosynthesis of polar lipids in Archaea are EC 1.1.1.261 (sn-glycerol-1-phosphate dehydrogenase), EC 2.5.1.42 (geranylgeranylglycerol-phosphate geranylgeranyltransferase) and EC 2.7.7.67 (CDP-archaeol synthase), which lead to the formation of CDP-unsaturated archaeol. The final step in the pathway involves the addition of L-serine, with concomitant removal of CMP, leading to the production of unsaturated archaetidylserine [5].
